segments.text: Hello and thank you for coming.
segments.speaker: SPEAKER_10

segments.text: The drug abuse epidemic is a humanitarian crisis that deserves just as much urgency as we gave to the COVID-19 pandemic.
segments.speaker: SPEAKER_10

segments.text: Instead, every day, people on our streets are dying of overdose and drug-related harm.
segments.speaker: SPEAKER_10

segments.text: It's time to face the facts.
segments.speaker: SPEAKER_10

segments.text: What we've been doing these past years isn't working.
segments.speaker: SPEAKER_10

segments.text: Year over year, overdose deaths rose by 72%.
segments.speaker: SPEAKER_10

segments.text: And no neighborhood has been untouched by the scourge of the drug abuse epidemic.
segments.speaker: SPEAKER_10

segments.text: Recently I signed an opioid settlement against producers and sellers of opioids to help remedy some of the harm caused.
segments.speaker: SPEAKER_10

segments.text: But in Seattle, right before our eyes, public drug use has sadly become normal.
segments.speaker: SPEAKER_10

segments.text: Our buses are unhealthy to use, our transit centers feel unsafe to wait in, and people walking down the street feel afraid.
segments.speaker: SPEAKER_10

segments.text: Children see it and look to adults for explanation, but usually they learn silence and ignoring.
segments.speaker: SPEAKER_10

segments.text: Not because they don't care, but because everyday people need government leaders to help.
segments.speaker: SPEAKER_10

segments.text: Open air drug markets now freely exist and overdose calls have skyrocketed.
segments.speaker: SPEAKER_10

segments.text: Enough is enough.
segments.speaker: SPEAKER_10

segments.text: We need to reclaim our public spaces, all of them.
segments.speaker: SPEAKER_10

segments.text: We need to intervene in the lives of people who are suffering and to do that we must see them and say that what they're doing in public is not okay for them or for us collectively.
segments.speaker: SPEAKER_10

segments.text: Together with Councilmember Nelson and Councilmember Peterson, we are proposing legislation this week to discourage public use.
segments.speaker: SPEAKER_10

segments.text: by of drugs by making it a prosecutable crime.
segments.speaker: SPEAKER_10

segments.text: This legislation is modeled after the recent Bellingham ordinance to reaffirm that public consumption of drugs is not acceptable.
segments.speaker: SPEAKER_10

segments.text: We need this tool to keep public spaces safe and reestablish what is accepted behavior.
segments.speaker: SPEAKER_10

segments.text: And frankly, we need investment from the state to open more beds and treatment facilities and invest in in custody treatment.
segments.speaker: SPEAKER_10

segments.text: I turn it over now to Council Member Nelson and then Council Member Peterson will take questions at the end.

segments.text: Thank you.
